DIV2.P:
CONFUSION, TOWNSEND! I have discovered the plot—I have got a clue to the whole matter. I am, I per∣ceive, a very catspaw. I am made the convenient cloak to conceal the passion of another. Yes, TOWNSEND, I saw CARLISLE at the very farthest end of DE GREY's garden in earnest conversa∣tion with LUCIA: at my approach he turned into a different walk, and went into the house. I overtook the guilty fair one, and caught her in the very act of reading ELOISA to ABELARD; which is as much as to say, if I can't talk with him, I can at least write a letter to him;

and I dare say they do correspond: every body in this family scribbles, and I don't at all doubt but there is fine flourishing penwork going forward be∣tween LUCIA and CARLISLE. As to the first, I only walked quickly by her, without deigning to speak, and I pulled off my hat with unusual respect, as much as to say—Oh, oh, my young lady, have I caught you! I shall repeat the same behaviour when I meet her again, and then it is impossible she should mistake my meaning. With re∣spect to the Captain, whom I honour as a friend and gentleman, in every other matter, his life is not worth sixpence, for he must as surely die this night, as that he insulted me this day; or else he must injure me still more, by taking me off. I only write this to you, TOWN∣SEND, just to account for any delay in my correspondence, should it be my fate

instead of his. In that case I desire you will be at the breaking open my will, because you are mentioned therein, by
